WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.040
 Okay, so now that we've gotten through the definitions,

00:00:03.040 --> 00:00:05.480
 let's work into some sample code.

00:00:05.480 --> 00:00:06.780
 But hey, look at this.

00:00:06.780 --> 00:00:09.860
 We've got ourselves a cookie cutter and some cookies.

00:00:09.860 --> 00:00:14.080
 So remember that a class is a template.

00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:15.760
 It's not the actual thing.

00:00:15.760 --> 00:00:19.920
 An object is an instance of a class.

00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:22.700
 So you have to take the class and do something

00:00:22.700 --> 00:00:24.160
 to make the object.

00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:26.640
 And actually, you can see here's some other classes.

00:00:26.640 --> 00:00:28.800
 There's clearly a sort of a snowflake class

00:00:28.800 --> 00:00:30.800
 and a gingerbread man class.

00:00:30.800 --> 00:00:32.720
 That's an object, object, object.

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:35.960
 Somewhere out here, there is a snowflake class

00:00:35.960 --> 00:00:37.660
 and a gingerbread class.

00:00:37.660 --> 00:00:41.480
 But we got a snowman object and a snowman object

00:00:41.480 --> 00:00:42.580
 and a snowman class.

00:00:42.580 --> 00:00:44.740
 So class is the template.

00:00:44.740 --> 00:00:49.520
 Object is the instance.

00:00:49.520 --> 00:00:50.800
 So here's a bit of Python code.

00:00:50.800 --> 00:00:53.640
 So let's take a look at what we got here.

00:00:53.640 --> 00:00:56.360
 Class is a new reserved word, kind of like def.

00:00:56.360 --> 00:00:57.680
 We have the name of the class.

00:00:57.680 --> 00:00:59.340
 That is a name that we choose.

00:00:59.340 --> 00:01:01.940
 That's the name by which we'll refer to this class

00:01:01.940 --> 00:01:04.080
 for the rest of this program.

00:01:04.080 --> 00:01:05.980
 And it has a colon at the end of it,

00:01:05.980 --> 00:01:08.140
 and which means it starts an indented block,

00:01:08.140 --> 00:01:10.360
 which ends when we deindent.

00:01:10.360 --> 00:01:12.420
 Inside the class, there are generally two things.

00:01:12.420 --> 00:01:14.080
 There is some data, and this just looks like

00:01:14.080 --> 00:01:17.160
 an assignment statement in the class, x equals zero.

00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:18.480
 And then there is a def.

00:01:18.480 --> 00:01:20.800
 Def, this looks just like a function,

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:23.720
 and then it starts with a def, has a colon, indents.

00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:26.000
 So that function finishes right there.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:28.180
 The difference is this is a method

00:01:28.180 --> 00:01:30.320
 because it lives inside of a class.

00:01:30.320 --> 00:01:32.780
 And so there is no function called party.

00:01:32.780 --> 00:01:37.220
 There's a function called party within party animal class.

00:01:37.220 --> 00:01:39.640
 And we'll talk in a second about this self thing.

00:01:39.640 --> 00:01:41.540
 It is the way that inside this code

00:01:41.540 --> 00:01:44.440
 we refer back to that variable.

00:01:44.440 --> 00:01:46.640
 So this is not actually executing any code.

00:01:46.640 --> 00:01:48.780
 It's sort of remembering the template,

00:01:48.780 --> 00:01:51.440
 defining the class party animal.

00:01:51.440 --> 00:01:53.540
 This is what we call constructing.

00:01:53.540 --> 00:01:56.580
 We're constructing, using the party animal template

00:01:56.580 --> 00:01:59.240
 or class, we are making a party animal.

00:01:59.240 --> 00:02:03.340
 And then once we make that, we stick it in the variable an.

00:02:03.340 --> 00:02:06.260
 And then we're going to call this party animal,

00:02:06.260 --> 00:02:09.840
 this party method, three times one, two, three.

00:02:09.840 --> 00:02:12.360
 Now this self thing, and we'll take a look at the self.

00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:16.040
 The self ends up being an alias of an.

00:02:16.040 --> 00:02:17.680
 And so you can look at this syntax.

00:02:17.680 --> 00:02:20.240
 It's just kind of an equivalent of this syntax.

00:02:20.240 --> 00:02:22.200
 It's calling the party method

00:02:22.200 --> 00:02:24.120
 within the party animal class

00:02:24.120 --> 00:02:27.520
 and passing the instance in as the first parameter.

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:31.400
 And so self ends up being an alias of an

00:02:31.400 --> 00:02:32.920
 each time these are called.

00:02:32.920 --> 00:02:37.040
 This syntax is a short version of that syntax.

00:02:37.040 --> 00:02:39.200
 So if we watch how this executes,

00:02:39.200 --> 00:02:43.240
 it starts up here, it just defines it,

00:02:43.240 --> 00:02:45.840
 and then we construct it.

00:02:45.840 --> 00:02:48.840
 And that's what basically constructing it,

00:02:48.840 --> 00:02:51.400
 we know how to construct it because we look at the class

00:02:51.400 --> 00:02:54.440
 and we make a variable x, we make some code party,

00:02:54.440 --> 00:02:55.800
 and then we construct that.

00:02:55.800 --> 00:02:57.160
 That's what the party animal does.

00:02:57.160 --> 00:02:59.640
 And then we assign that into an.

00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:03.120
 And so an is now pointing at that.

00:03:03.120 --> 00:03:05.640
 Then when we call the party method,

00:03:05.640 --> 00:03:09.640
 that basically takes this an and passes it in

00:03:09.640 --> 00:03:13.520
 as the first parameter, which is used as self.

00:03:13.520 --> 00:03:16.800
 And so self.x, which is what we're doing

00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:19.480
 in this line right here, self.x is a variable.

00:03:19.480 --> 00:03:24.480
 x starts out as zero, x starts out as zero,

00:03:24.480 --> 00:03:26.920
 because when it was constructed it was set to zero.

00:03:26.920 --> 00:03:29.880
 So we're in here, an is an alias of self.

00:03:29.880 --> 00:03:32.360
 And now it looks up self.x, which is zero,

00:03:32.360 --> 00:03:34.920
 adds one to it, and so this becomes one.

00:03:34.920 --> 00:03:37.840
 And then we print so far, so far one.

00:03:37.840 --> 00:03:39.440
 And then the code returns and it goes down

00:03:39.440 --> 00:03:40.760
 and does it again.

00:03:40.760 --> 00:03:44.080
 And x becomes two, prints out so far two,

00:03:44.080 --> 00:03:47.680
 comes back down, and does the last time, calls it again.

00:03:47.680 --> 00:03:50.840
 Self.x is two, add one to it and stick it back in,

00:03:50.840 --> 00:03:53.760
 so this becomes three, and we print out three.

00:03:53.760 --> 00:03:55.400
 And then the program finishes.

00:03:55.400 --> 00:03:59.400
 And so you can think of this as constructing the object

00:03:59.400 --> 00:04:03.480
 and then associating it with this an variable.

00:04:03.480 --> 00:04:07.920
 Now, we've created this object, we can play around

00:04:07.920 --> 00:04:10.440
 with things we've played around before with Durantype.

00:04:10.440 --> 00:04:14.480
 We use Durantype to kind of inspect variables

00:04:14.480 --> 00:04:17.280
 and types and objects.

00:04:17.280 --> 00:04:20.480
 So we've been using objects all along.

00:04:20.480 --> 00:04:23.440
 We, this code here says, hey, make me an empty list.

00:04:23.440 --> 00:04:25.800
 Well, it turns out that what we're saying

00:04:25.800 --> 00:04:30.040
 is there is already a list class inside of Python

00:04:30.040 --> 00:04:32.400
 and we're constructing an empty list.

00:04:32.400 --> 00:04:34.680
 And when we get back this empty list,

00:04:34.680 --> 00:04:37.040
 we're assigning that into x.

00:04:37.040 --> 00:04:41.240
 So x, in a sense, contains or points to an empty list.

00:04:41.240 --> 00:04:43.220
 So then we say, hey, what is in x?

00:04:43.220 --> 00:04:44.480
 What kind of thing is x?

00:04:44.480 --> 00:04:45.800
 Well, it's a list.

00:04:45.800 --> 00:04:47.560
 This is a thing, it's a list type.

00:04:47.560 --> 00:04:50.080
 Let's have a list of things in them.

00:04:50.080 --> 00:04:53.240
 And use append and all the things we've been doing before,

00:04:53.240 --> 00:04:54.360
 they're just objects.

00:04:54.360 --> 00:04:56.680
 And then the dir, if you remember the dir,

00:04:56.680 --> 00:04:59.000
 the dir is the capabilities.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:00.920
 And there's all these internal capabilities

00:05:00.920 --> 00:05:04.040
 that do things like implement the bracket operator, et cetera,

00:05:04.040 --> 00:05:05.580
 those double underscore ones.

00:05:05.580 --> 00:05:07.640
 We can ignore them, although you can even look them up

00:05:07.640 --> 00:05:09.640
 and figure out what they mean if you feel like it.

00:05:09.640 --> 00:05:13.200
 But the methods that we tend to call are in this class.

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:18.200
 And so things like x.sort, I've always told you,

00:05:18.200 --> 00:05:21.260
 that is the sort method within the x thing.

00:05:21.260 --> 00:05:23.520
 And the dot operator is the operator

00:05:23.520 --> 00:05:26.240
 that we use to look something up within an object.

00:05:26.240 --> 00:05:29.200
 And so you've been using the syntax all along.

00:05:29.200 --> 00:05:33.480
 x.sort, dictionary.items, all of those are methods

00:05:33.480 --> 00:05:36.080
 within the corresponding class.

00:05:36.080 --> 00:05:39.000
 If we take a look at this line of code

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:41.160
 that we've been doing for a very long time,

00:05:41.160 --> 00:05:43.600
 which says, oh, stick hello there into y.

00:05:43.600 --> 00:05:47.640
 If I reword that as more OO or object-oriented,

00:05:47.640 --> 00:05:49.960
 what this single quote does says,

00:05:49.960 --> 00:05:54.560
 make me a string object and put some text in it,

00:05:54.560 --> 00:05:57.280
 and then when that is done being constructed,

00:05:57.280 --> 00:05:59.640
 stick that into y, right?

00:05:59.640 --> 00:06:03.880
 And so y now points to a string object

00:06:03.880 --> 00:06:06.560
 that's been pre-initialized to the string hello there.

00:06:06.560 --> 00:06:09.440
 Now that's a long way of saying hello there ends up in y.

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:12.320
 But in OO terms we can talk about that.

00:06:12.320 --> 00:06:14.640
 If we do a dir of that, we see a whole bunch

00:06:14.640 --> 00:06:18.440
 of internal methods, which have double underscores.

00:06:18.440 --> 00:06:20.720
 And then we see all kinds of methods that we've been using.

00:06:20.720 --> 00:06:23.120
 We've been using methods like upper.

00:06:23.120 --> 00:06:25.480
 We've been using methods like find.

00:06:25.480 --> 00:06:30.480
 We've been using methods like rstrip, right?

00:06:30.480 --> 00:06:32.000
 We've been using these methods.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:37.000
 So we're going to like y.rstrip, parenthesis.

00:06:37.180 --> 00:06:40.680
 Again, that's a method, that's an object.

00:06:40.680 --> 00:06:42.020
 Not a class, it's an object.

00:06:42.020 --> 00:06:44.520
 And that is the object lookup operator.

00:06:44.520 --> 00:06:49.960
 Now if we do the same thing to code that we've built,

00:06:49.960 --> 00:06:51.260
 or a class that we've built.

00:06:51.260 --> 00:06:54.000
 So now we have a party animal class.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:56.640
 Remember this up to here is just definition.

00:06:56.640 --> 00:06:59.560
 Now we construct it and we store it in an.

00:06:59.560 --> 00:07:02.060
 So an is a variable that contains an object

00:07:02.060 --> 00:07:03.820
 of type party animal.

00:07:03.820 --> 00:07:07.240
 We ask it what type it is and it prints out here.

00:07:07.240 --> 00:07:09.520
 It says this is a class.

00:07:09.520 --> 00:07:11.720
 And it's main underscore party animal.

00:07:11.720 --> 00:07:14.600
 And this whole thing here is the underscore main.

00:07:14.600 --> 00:07:16.280
 It's scoped underscore main.

00:07:16.280 --> 00:07:19.040
 But you can see that you have made a new type.

00:07:19.040 --> 00:07:21.920
 You built a type by using this class keyword.

00:07:21.920 --> 00:07:23.040
 And then we use the dir.

00:07:23.040 --> 00:07:25.380
 Remember dir looks for capabilities.

00:07:25.380 --> 00:07:30.380
 And again, you will see a whole bunch of underscore things.

00:07:30.380 --> 00:07:32.680
 They have meaning, you can look them up.

00:07:32.680 --> 00:07:34.240
 But eventually you'll see the two things

00:07:34.240 --> 00:07:35.240
 that you've put in it.

00:07:35.240 --> 00:07:38.320
 One is the method party, and the other is the attribute,

00:07:38.320 --> 00:07:39.800
 or field X.

00:07:39.800 --> 00:07:44.400
 And again, these are the things that you can say an.x,

00:07:44.400 --> 00:07:47.020
 or an.party.

00:07:47.020 --> 00:07:50.760
 'Cause this dot is the object operator,

00:07:50.760 --> 00:07:52.840
 the object lookup operator that says,

00:07:52.840 --> 00:07:55.560
 look up in the object an the thing X,

00:07:55.560 --> 00:07:58.360
 or look up in the object an the thing party.

00:07:58.360 --> 00:07:59.200
 Okay?

00:08:01.640 --> 00:08:03.160
 So up next we'll talk a little bit

00:08:03.160 --> 00:08:05.960
 about how objects are created and destroyed.

00:08:05.960 --> 00:08:08.180
 We also call that object life cycle.

